le of foreign aid and transnational penetration. His analysis show, however, that these motives for alignment are relatively less important. In his conclusion, he examines the implications of "balance of threat" for U.S. foreign policy.‹/p›  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAlliances. 0aInternational relations. 4aInternational Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History.  a(neo)realist theory of international relations.  aalliance formation.  aalliances middle east.  aalliances.  aameria cold war.  abaghdad pact.  abooks on foreign policy.  abooks on international relations.  acamp david accords.  acold war history.  acold war policy.  acurrent affairs.  adiplomacy.  adiplomatic relations theories.  adiplomatic relations.  aforeign policy.  ahistory of political theory.  ahistory of the six day war.  ahow to make foreign policy.  ahow to start an alliance.  ainternational affairs.  ainternational politics.  ainternational relations theory.  ainternational relations.  ainternational security.  amiddle east 1945.  amiddle east 1955.  amiddle east 1979.  amiddle east cold war.  amiddle east foreign policy.  amiddle east in the 60s.  amiddle east politics.  amiddle eastern politics.  amilitary history.  apolitical theory.  asix day war.  atheory of international politics.  atreaties and alliances.  awhat is an allliance.  awhat is the camp david accord.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146999240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801469992423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801469992/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL